<subSubSection id="C3430099237B6050D7E0F872FCA3A662" pageId="3" pageNumber="85" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BE65312237B6050D7E0F872FE14A2DA" blockId="3.[55,704,1928,1952]" box="[454,467,1928,1951]" pageId="3" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis id="B92D8F00237B6050D7E0F872FE14A2DA" box="[454,467,1928,1951]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="85">–</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE65312237B6050D7FCF873FCECA48A" blockId="3.[55,704,1928,1952]" lastBlockId="3.[746,1396,170,807]" pageId="3" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis id="B92D8F00237B6050D7FCF873FD92A2E5" box="[474,597,1928,1952]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="85">B. molensis</emphasis>
Wild, endemic of the southern serpentines of the Great South Dyke in Zimbabwe, is closely allied and very similar to the novelty 
<taxonomicName id="4C592891237B6050D37AFF33FC8AA5BB" authorityName="Dominique Champluvier" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Barleria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="85" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glutinosa">
<emphasis id="B92D8F00237B6050D37AFF33FC8AA5BB" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="85">B. glutinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; it can be considered as a vicariant species (fig. 4). There are twenty endemic species of the serpentines of the Great Dyke; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC82EE3237B6050D553FED8FC30A47F" author="Wild. H." box="[885,1015,290,314]" journalOrPublisher="Kirkia" pageId="3" pageNumber="85" pagination="49 - 86" part="5" refId="ref9386" refString="Wild. H. (1965) The flora of the Great Dyke of Southern Rhodesia with special reference to the serpentine soils. Kirkia 5: 49 - 86." title="The flora of the Great Dyke of Southern Rhodesia with special reference to the serpentine soils" type="journal article" year="1965">Wild (1965)</bibRefCitation>
explains that these endemics could have arosen by depletion of “various metal non-tolerant biotypes which formerly allowed the species to exploit a greater variety of habitats”, species of which only serpentine-tolerant biotypes would have survived on the deposits of the Great Dyke.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE65312237B6050D536FE27FADEA729" blockId="3.[746,1396,170,807]" pageId="3" pageNumber="85">
Following 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC82EE3237B6050D5A1FE27FB7CA4B0" box="[903,1211,477,501]" pageId="3" pageNumber="85" refId="ref9206" refString="Balkwill M. - J., Balkwill K. (1997) Delimitation and infrageneric classification of Barleria (Acanthaceae). Kew Bulletin 52: 535 - 573. [available at http: // www. jstor. org / pss / 4110286]" type="journal article">Balkwill &amp; Balkwill (1997)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="B92D8F00237B6050D2EFFE27FA80A4B0" box="[1225,1351,477,501]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="85">B. molensis</emphasis>
belongs to sect. 
<taxonomicName id="4C592891237B6050D5A3FE01FC18A756" baseAuthorityName="Balkwill &amp; Balkwill" baseAuthorityYear="1997" box="[901,991,507,531]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Barleria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="85" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92D8F00237B6050D5A3FE01FC18A756" box="[901,991,507,531]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="85">Barleria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; the closely related 
<taxonomicName id="4C592891237B6050D2E7FE01FA82A756" authorityName="Dominique Champluvier" authorityYear="2011" box="[1217,1349,507,531]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Barleria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="85" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glutinosa">
<emphasis id="B92D8F00237B6050D2E7FE01FA82A756" box="[1217,1349,507,531]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="85">B. glutinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can therefore be considered as a member of that section, as it has spiny bracteoles, solitary flowers, a corolla with 2 + 3 configuration, two fertile stamens and three staminodes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE65312237B6050D536FD80FCA3A662" blockId="3.[746,1396,170,807]" pageId="3" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis id="B92D8F00237B6050D536FD80FC5DA7D4" box="[784,922,634,657]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="85">B. aromatica</emphasis>
, from Zimbabwe, superficially resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C592891237B6050D37AFD80FC8AA7F5" authorityName="Dominique Champluvier" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Barleria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="85" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glutinosa">
<emphasis id="B92D8F00237B6050D37AFD80FC8AA7F5" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="85">B. glutinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the plant is not at all glandulous, the leaves are 2 × 0.6 cm, the flowers are rather smaller, with the outer calyx lobe 13 × 6 mm, the corolla tube 2.5 cm long, the upper lobes 1.5 × 0.8 cm, the lower one 1.5 × 1.1 cm and the lateral ones 1.5 × 1 cm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
